Identifying differentially accessible peaks with ArchR¶

  1. Proprocessing
    • Create arrowfiles with merged lung samples and spleen samples
    • Infer doublets
    • Create an ArchRProject
    • Data QC
  2. Dimensionality reduction and clustering
    • correct batch effect
  3. Visualizing in a 2D UMAP embedding
  4. Annotate cells with cell type labels from expression data
  5. Call peaks for each cell type
  6. DA analysis across cell types
  7. DA analysis between tissues

1 Proprocessing chromatin accessibility data¶

In [6]:
## Build ArchR objects

ArrowFiles <- createArrowFiles(
    # perform QC and filtering
  inputFiles = c(sprintf("%s/AGG_lungs/%s", work.dir, "atac_fragments.tsv.gz"),
                 sprintf("%s/AGG_spleens/%s", work.dir, "atac_fragments.tsv.gz")),
  sampleNames = c("lungs","spleens"),
  minTSS = 4, 
  minFrags = 1000, 
  addTileMat = TRUE,
  addGeneScoreMat = TRUE
)

doubScores <- addDoubletScores
    # detect doublets
  input = ArrowFiles,
  k = 10, #Refers to how many cells near a "pseudo-doublet" to count.
  knnMethod = "UMAP", #Refers to the embedding to use for nearest neighbor search.
  LSIMethod = 1
)

proj <- ArchRProject(
  ArrowFiles = ArrowFiles, 
  outputDirectory = "all_samples",
  copyArrows = TRUE #This is recommened so that you maintain an unaltered copy for later usage.
)
proj <- filterDoublets(ArchRProj = proj)

## Normalization, dimensional reduction, and UMAP embedding

proj <- addIterativeLSI(ArchRProj = proj, useMatrix = "TileMatrix", name = "IterativeLSI")

proj <- addClusters(input = proj, reducedDims = "IterativeLSI")

proj <- addUMAP(ArchRProj = proj, reducedDims = "IterativeLSI")

Batch effects not corrected for downstream analysis¶

The correction with Harmony seems to exacerbate the difference between lungs and spleens, so the following analysis was performed on the uncorrected one.

Evaluate the consistency between clusters and cell type labels from RNA data¶

The unsupervised clustering results on chromatin accessibility data shows overall consistency with cell type labels obtained from scRNA-seq data.

5 Peak calling¶

  • Make pseudobulk replicates by adding group coverages for each cell type
  • Call peaks using MACS2
  • Quantify reads in peaks

Note: no unusual symbols shall be included in the group names, otherwise no hdf5 file can be found.
